'''Hafizud Dean Khan''' is a [[Fiji]]an businessman, and a former [[Senate of Fiji|Senator]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Fiji Muslim League unhappy "Prophet" cartoon reprinted|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NewsLibrary&p_multi=BBAB&d_place=BBAB&p_theme=newslibrary2&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=10F9CF87715C94D8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=24 January 2011|newspaper=Fijilive via [[BBC]]|date=6 February 2006}}</ref>  and president of the Muslim League.<ref>{{cite news|title=Muslims observe Ramadan|url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=153423|accessdate=24 January 2011|newspaper=[[Fiji Times]]|date=12 August 2010|author=Riteshni Singh}}</ref>   Appointed to the Senate on 13 July 2005 to fill a vacancy caused by the death of Dr [[Ahmed Ali (politician)|Ahmed Ali]], Khan became one of the 9 out of 32 Senators nominated by the [[Prime Minister of Fiji|Prime Minister]] (a further 14 are chosen by the [[Great Council of Chiefs]], 8 by the [[Leader of the Opposition (Fiji)|Leader of the Opposition]], and 1 by the [[Council of Rotuma]]).  Khan was formally sworn in on 22 August 2005.  In June 2006, he became [[Vice-President of the Senate (Fiji)|Vice-President of the Senate]] and served in this capacity until the Senate was forcibly dissolved one day after the [[2006 Fijian coup d'état|military coup]] of 5 December 2006.

Khan is Chairman of the [[Hexagon group of companies]], and has served in the past as Chairman of the [[Fiji Sugar Corporation]] and of the [[Fiji Hotel Association]].  He is also a member of the [[Fiji National Tourism Council]], and serves on the National Advisory Committee for multi-ethnic affairs, and on the National Reconciliation Committee.

== Disaster relief for India and Pakistan ==
{{Wikiquotepar|Hafiz Khan}}
On 14 October, 2005, Khan launched a national appeal for funds to assist with relief efforts in the wake of the devastating [[2005 Kashmir earthquake|earthquake]] that struck [[Kashmir]], on the [[India]]/[[Pakistan]] border on 8 October, 2005.  The money raised by the Fiji Muslim League would complement the [[Fijian dollar|F$90,000]] pledged by the Fijian government, Khan said.

