'''Yemi Idowu''',<ref>{{cite web|author=Stocks |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=79222761&privcapId=30142044 |title=Stocks |publisher=Bloomberg |date= |accessdate=2016-12-16}}</ref> or '''Oluyemi Idowu''', (born 3 December 1968) is a [[Nigeria]]n entrepreneur, industrialist and philanthropist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pulse.ng/sports/football/nigeria-u-23-dream-team-vi-finally-leaves-united-states-players-refused-small-planes-id5342475.html|title=Nigeria U-23: Dream Team VI finally leaves United States, players refused small planes|last=Dede|first=Steve|access-date=2018-06-11|language=en-US}}</ref>

==Early life and education==
Idowu was born in [[Ibadan]], Nigeria to the Late Chief (Dr) Nathaniel Olabiyi Idowu (OFR), the Mayeloye and the Okanlomo of Ibadan land. Yemi spent his early years schooling in the [[United Kingdom]] and participated actively in sports at the youth level.{{cn|date=June 2018}}

An alumnus of the [[Harvard Business School]] Executive Education Program, Idowu holds a Bachelor of Science in Accounts and Financial Analysis from the [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] University, England and a Post Graduate Diploma in Human Resource Management.{{cn|date=June 2018}}

He is a member of the [[Chartered Institute of Personnel and Development|Institute of Personnel Management]]. After his university education, he worked as a Business Development Manager for Africa and the Middle East at Anglo European Equipment, London.{{cn|date=June 2018}}

==Business career and sports==
Idowu is an accomplished businessman having served on the board of various companies. Idowu founded Aircom Nigeria Limited in 1992 and serves as the Managing Director till date.

Until July 2014, Idowu served as a [[non-executive Director]] with [[Sterling Bank (Nigeria)]] PLC from its inception in 2005 and was a onetime Chairman of Sterling Capital <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sterlingcapitalng.com/index2.php?pageSt=46&url=&pCat=aboutus&all=none |title=Sterling Capital Markets Ltd |publisher=Sterlingcapitalng.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-16}}</ref> as well as being the Vice Chairman of NBM Bank between 1999 and 2005.

Idowu also sat on the governing council of the Bank Directors Association of Nigeria (BDAN) <ref>{{cite web|author=by adefaye |url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2011/10/bank-directors-and-future-of-banking-in-nigeria/ |title=Bank Directors and future of banking in Nigeria - Vanguard News |publisher=Vanguardngr.com |date=2011-10-24 |accessdate=2016-12-16}}</ref> as its General Secretary between 2009 and 2014. Idowu also serves as Chairman Leyland Nigeria (Nigeria’s largest indigenous automobile assembly plant) and is a Director of the Lagos Junior League and the current Chairman of Nathaniel Boys Football Club <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nigerianeye.com/2016/08/yemi-idowus-nath-boys-fc-are-lagos.html |title=Yemi Idowu's Nath Boys FC are Lagos Metro Pro League Champions &#124; Nigeria News Today. Your online Nigerian Newspaper |publisher=Nigerianeye.com |date=2012-06-09 |accessdate=2016-12-16}}</ref>  where the likes of [[Leicester City F.C.]] midfield maestro [[Wilfred Ndidi]] who played for [[Genk]] in the [[Belgian Pro League]] started their careers from.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://africanfootball.com/news/634121/Ndidis-Genk-sneak-through-to-next-round-of-Europa-League |title=Ndidi's Genk sneak through to next round of Europa League - Belgium |publisher=Africanfootball.com |date=2016-07-21 |accessdate=2016-12-16}}</ref>

Idowu has been involved in sports philanthropy and grassroots sports development for many years. As a result, he was appointed Board Chairman of the Nigerian Academicals Sports Committee (NASCOM) - a presidential committee in November 2012.{{cn|date=June 2018}}

In his capacity as Chairman of the board of NASCOM,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ynaija.com/yemi-idowu-ohimai-amaize-others-make-reconstituted-board-of-nigeria-academicals-sports-committee/ |title=Yemi Idowu, Ohimai Amaize, others make reconstituted board of Nigeria Academicals Sports Committee |publisher=YNaija |date= |accessdate=2016-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201312020322.html|title=Nigeria: Yemi Idowu - School Sports Will Stop Age Cheats|date=2013-12-02|work=This Day (Lagos)|access-date=2018-06-11}}</ref> Yemi Idowu was instrumental in initiating the Rhythm N' Play campaign <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newtimes.co.rw/section/article/2013-06-14/44077/ |title=President Goodluck Jonathan appoints actor ambassador - The New Times &#124; Rwanda |publisher=The New Times |date=2013-06-14 |accessdate=2016-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=by adekunle |url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2013/05/jonathan-launches-rhythm-n-play-june-6/ |title=Jonathan launches Rhythm ‘N’ Play June 6 - Vanguard News |publisher=Vanguardngr.com |date=2013-05-24 |accessdate=2016-12-16}}</ref> - a grassroot sports mobilization campaign targeted at bringing an additional 2 million Nigeria school children into sports within a two-year period. Former Nigerian President [[Goodluck Jonathan]] launched the campaign in Abuja on 6 June 2013.

Idowu is involved in infrastructure sustainability and security as tools to developing and sustaining Mega cities in Africa and on 10 November 2015 he was appointed a member of the Board of Trustees of the Lagos State Security Trust Fund <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804010251/http://lsstf.lagosstate.gov.ng:80/2016/07/12/6436/|title=Wayback Machine|date=2016-08-04|access-date=2018-06-11}}</ref>  alongside [[Herbert Wigwe]], Opeyemi Agbaje, Gbolahan Lawal and Phillip Oduozua by his Excellency [[Akinwunmi Ambode]] the [[Lagos State Governor]].

